    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, n. <citedRange>3</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.340</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>032400</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Εὐγα_"><seg part="I">Εὐ<unclear>γα</unclear></seg></name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>   
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This is probably, as Ferri thought, the beginning of a personal name, indicating the owner of the altar, as no divine name seems to begin with those letters.
	           For other such mentions, see commentary at <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr032000</ref>.</p>
	           <p>This personal name might be restored either as <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὔγαμος</foreign>, which is attested once at Rhodes in the second century BC and several 
	           times in various regions in the Late Empire, or better as <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὐγάμων</foreign>, which is known for a poet having composed a 
	               <foreign rend="italic">Telegonia </foreign> about 565 BC at Battos' court to honour the Battiad family. However, other derived names would also be possible.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
